K Nearest Neighbors Project¶

In this project, we'll be constructing a K Nearest Neighbors (KNN) machine learning algorithm on an artificial data set. Using the features of the data, we'll attempt to classify the TARGET CLASS of an observation based on its similarity to other observations in the data set.

Voila - gotta love artificial data!

  • These feature distributions look nearly perfect, mostly normally distributed, and centered on 0. We should be able to move forward with confidence in this data set's normality.

  • It is worth noting that the feature-wise correlations in this data set are generally quite weak. A lack of intercorrelated features emphasizes the neccessity for a strong KNN model, which we'll develop in the next section of this project.

Standardize the Variables¶

Now it's time to standardize the features of this data set; this involves scaling each feature to its respective unit variance.

In [4]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler()

# Computes mean / SD for transformation
scaler.fit(data.drop(["TARGET CLASS"], axis = 1))
Out[4]:

scaled_data = scaler.transform(data.drop(["TARGET CLASS"], axis = 1))

Train Test Split¶

Next, we'll need to stratify the data set into training and test components. We'll use 30% of the data as a test-split.

In [7]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
In [8]:
X = sc_data
y = data["TARGET CLASS"]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3)

Using KNN¶

We're finally ready to build our KNN model. We'll start with a n_neighbors value of 1, but that's just to get us going. We'll eventually optimize the model to reduce the implicit bias in our model.

In [9]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 1)

# Fit model to training data
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[9]:
KNeighborsClassifier(algorithm='auto', leaf_size=30, metric='minkowski',
           metric_params=None, n_jobs=None, n_neighbors=1, p=2,
           weights='uniform')
In [10]:
# Use fit to predict test values for TARGET CLASS
preds = knn.predict(X_test)

Predictions and Evaluations¶

Let's evaluate our KNN model!

In [11]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

print(classification_report(y_test, preds))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.74      0.74      0.74       147
           1       0.75      0.75      0.75       153

   micro avg       0.74      0.74      0.74       300
   macro avg       0.74      0.74      0.74       300
weighted avg       0.74      0.74      0.74       300

Hmm, ok. A precision rate of 76% is not all that stellar, but we planned for this. The model as it presently exists is not optimized to reduce bias - far from it, in fact. We'll need to choose a more meaningful n_neighbors value.

Choosing a K Value¶

Using the elbow method we'll:

  • Loop through a range of possible n_neighbors values (in this case 1-100)
  • Calculate the average error rate at each value
  • Select the optimized value.
In [12]:
# We'll be adding error rates to this empty list
errors = []

# Loop through n_neighbors 1-100 and append average error rate to errors
for k in range(1, 100):
    
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = k)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    predictions = knn.predict(X_test)
    errors.append(np.mean(predictions != y_test))
In [13]:
sns.set_style("white")
plt.figure(figsize = (18,10))
p3 = sns.scatterplot(x = range(1,100), y = errors, s = 65)
p3.set_xlabel("K")
p3.set_ylabel("Error Rate")
Out[13]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Error Rate')
In [14]:
# Optimized N-Neighbors value from errors list
newK = (errors.index(min(errors)) + 1)

newK
Out[14]:
84

Using this value, we'll retrain, fit, and predict a KNN model to predict TARGET CLASS on the test data.

Retraining¶

In [15]:
uknn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = newK)

uknn.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[15]:
KNeighborsClassifier(algorithm='auto', leaf_size=30, metric='minkowski',
           metric_params=None, n_jobs=None, n_neighbors=84, p=2,
           weights='uniform')
In [16]:
upreds = uknn.predict(X_test)
In [17]:
print(classification_report(y_test, upreds))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.90      0.77      0.83       147
           1       0.80      0.92      0.86       153

   micro avg       0.84      0.84      0.84       300
   macro avg       0.85      0.84      0.84       300
weighted avg       0.85      0.84      0.84       300

We arrive at our optimized model, which is a marked improvement from our first attempt.
